issue.title: On OQS-OpenSSL integrated with Peer-to-Peer protocols
issue.body:
I saw that the oqs-demos repo offers a number of integrations of OQS-OpenSSL with client-server style applications. 
My question is if there is any (current or futurely planned) example of integration with an open source peer-to-peer protocol to evaluate how the post-quantum migration impacts other networking paradigms?

comment.body: Thanks for the additional thoughts, @geovandro . Any code base not actively maintained isn't exactly attractive as any introduction of QSC seems to require changes to such apps (or libs) -- and that isn't fun if no-one checks/confirms those changes. Blockchain apps generally make me shiver --too much nonsense done in the space. If you know a sensible one, please list it here. In turn, a reputable, maintained, cryptographically secured open peer-to-peer protocol -- why not? What about [tor](https://www.torproject.org)? But then again, that's already so slow that interesting/meaningful performance results/differences using different QSC algs probably won't cause interest. The added protection in turn might be... For performance testing, p2p filesharing apps might be more interesting. I personally just don't know any of them well enough to decide which one could meaningfully benefit from QSC. If you do, again, let's discuss further.

comment.body: The branch `OpenSSL3` is outdated: The current OpenSSL3 (provider) code is at https://github.com/open-quantum-safe/oqs-provider.
